## 1. Security

---

Risk — Prompt injection and adversarial input attacks

Impact —** Malicious inputs could manipulate model outputs, exfiltrate data embedded in responses, or bypass enterprise content filters — exposing member PII or proprietary financial data.

Mitigation — Implement input/output sanitization layers before Cohere API calls. Apply content filtering policies via North's agent autonomy controls. Log all prompts and completions for anomaly detection. Align to NIST AI RMF MANAGE 2.2.

Severity — 🔴 High

Frameworks —NIST AI RMF, SR 11-7

---

Risk — API key exposure and credential mismanagement

Impact — Exposed API credentials could allow unauthorized access to Cohere endpoints, enabling data extraction or generation of harmful content at enterprise scale.

Mitigation — Store credentials in enterprise secrets management (e.g., HashiCorp Vault). Rotate keys on a defined schedule. Enforce least-privilege access via IAM. Audit usage logs monthly.

Severity — 🔴 High

Frameworks — ISO 27001, NIST CSF

---

Risk — Model inference endpoint exposure

Impact — Publicly accessible or insufficiently protected inference endpoints could be probed to extract model behavior patterns or enable denial-of-service conditions.

Mitigation — Deploy Cohere via private VPC or on-premises using Model Vault. Restrict endpoint access to internal network only. Apply rate limiting and WAF rules at the API gateway layer.

Severity — 🟡 Medium

Frameworks — NIST AI RMF, ISO 27001

---

## 2. Privacy

---

Risk — Member PII ingested into RAG pipelines

Impact — If member financial data, SSNs, or account details are included in documents fed to Cohere's Embed or Rerank models, the platform may retain or expose that data outside enterprise control.

Mitigation — Enforce PII scrubbing before document ingestion using entity recognition pipelines. Apply data classification gates upstream of RAG workflows. Validate Cohere's 30-day SaaS log deletion policy against internal retention requirements.

Severity — 🔴 High

Frameworks — GLBA, CCPA, NIST Privacy Framework

---

Risk —Cross-tenant data leakage in SaaS deployment

Impact — SaaS deployment introduces residual risk of tenant isolation failure — member data could surface in another organization's query responses.

Mitigation — Prefer private VPC or on-premises deployment for member-data workloads. Review Cohere's SOC 2 Type II report and tenant isolation architecture documentation. Require contractual data processing addendum.

Severity — 🔴 High

Frameworks — SOC 2, ISO 27001

---

Risk — Model training on enterprise prompts

Impact — Without explicit contractual protections, enterprise query data submitted to Cohere could be used for model fine-tuning, violating member data agreements.

Mitigation — Require Data Processing Addendum (DPA) explicitly prohibiting training on customer data. Validate zero-retention configuration for SaaS usage. Review Cohere's enterprise data commitments documentation annually.

Severity — 🟡 Medium

Frameworks —GLBA, CCPA

---

## 3. Compliance

---

Risk — Regulatory examination readiness gap

Impact — Federal banking regulators (OCC, Federal Reserve) expect model risk management documentation aligned to SR 11-7. Undocumented Cohere deployments expose the institution to MRM examination findings.

Mitigation — Classify Cohere-powered models under the SR 11-7 model inventory. Document model purpose, inputs, outputs, and limitations. Conduct initial and ongoing model validation including conceptual soundness review and outcome analysis.

Severity — 🔴 High

Frameworks — SR 11-7, OCC

---

Risk — AI Act and emerging regulatory non-compliance

Impact — EU AI Act high-risk classification triggers mandatory conformity assessments, bias testing, and human oversight requirements. Financial services AI is explicitly in scope.

Mitigation — Conduct AI risk classification assessment per NIST AI RMF GOVERN 1.1 and EU AI Act Annex III criteria. Document intended use cases to support classification. Implement bias monitoring for credit, underwriting, or member-facing applications.

Severity — 🔴 High

Frameworks — EU AI Act, NIST AI RMF

---

Risk — ISO 42001 alignment gap

Impact — Cohere holds ISO 42001 certification; the enterprise may lack an equivalent AI management system, creating asymmetry in vendor versus internal governance maturity.

Mitigation —Use Cohere's ISO 42001 posture as a benchmark for internal AI management system development. Map existing AI governance policies to ISO 42001 controls. Identify gaps and build a remediation roadmap.

Severity — 🟡 Medium

Frameworks — ISO 42001

