## 4. Third-Party Risk

---

Risk — Vendor concentration and single-provider dependency

Impact — Deep integration of Cohere into enterprise workflows creates switching costs and business continuity exposure if Cohere experiences service disruption, acquisition, or pricing restructuring.

Mitigation — Maintain a multi-model strategy (cloud-agnostic architecture). Document fallback workflows for critical Cohere-dependent processes. Include SLA, uptime guarantees, and exit clauses in enterprise contract. Review vendor financial health annually.

Severity — 🔴 High

Frameworks — SR 11-7, NIST AI RMF

---

Risk — Insufficient vendor AI risk transparency

Impact — Limited visibility into Cohere's model training data, update cadence, and internal safety practices makes it difficult to assess downstream risk changes introduced by model updates.

Mitigation — Require advance notification of model version changes per contract terms. Conduct re-validation or regression testing after major model updates. Maintain a vendor AI risk dossier updated quarterly.

Severity — 🟡 Medium

Frameworks — SR 11-7

---

Risk — Fourth-party risk via Cohere's cloud infrastructure partners

Impact — Cohere deploys via AWS, Azure, GCP, and Oracle. Incidents at those providers cascade into Cohere availability, even for private deployment configurations.

Mitigation — Map Cohere's cloud infrastructure dependencies in the enterprise's fourth-party risk register. Assess provider concentration risk. Include Cohere in BCM/DR planning and test recovery runbooks annually.

Severity — 🟡 Medium

Frameworks — NIST CSF, ISO 27001

---

## 5. Data Protection

---

Risk — Data residency violations for regulated member data

Impact — If enterprise data leaves the defined geographic boundary (e.g., US-only for GLBA compliance), regulatory violations and member trust damage could result.

Mitigation — Configure Cohere deployment to enforce data residency via US-region VPC or on-premises Model Vault deployment. Validate residency configuration at implementation and after any infrastructure changes. Document in data flow diagrams.

Severity — 🔴 High

Frameworks — GLBA, CCPA, ISO 27001

---

Risk — Inadequate data retention and deletion controls

Impact — Cohere's SaaS platform deletes logs after 30 days by default, but flagged content is retained indefinitely. This may conflict with enterprise data lifecycle management policies.

Mitigation — Map Cohere's retention behavior to the enterprise data retention schedule. Escalate conflicts to the Privacy Office. For sensitive workloads, use private deployment where the enterprise controls all retention settings.

Severity — 🟡 Medium

Frameworks — GLBA, NIST Privacy Framework

---

Risk — Unstructured data governance in RAG pipelines

Impact — Documents ingested for retrieval may include stale, unauthorized, or sensitive content that gets surfaced to end users without proper access controls.

Mitigation — Implement document-level metadata tagging and access control before ingestion. Apply North's role-based access controls to limit retrieval scope by user role. Audit ingested document sources quarterly.

Severity — 🟢 Low

Frameworks — NIST AI RMF, ISO 27001

