## 6. Human Oversight

---

Risk — Automation bias in AI-assisted decisioning

Impact — Staff may over-rely on Cohere-generated outputs in member-facing decisions (claims, underwriting, service routing), reducing critical judgment and increasing error propagation at scale.

Mitigation — Establish human-in-the-loop review requirements for consequential decisions. Define clear escalation thresholds where AI output requires human sign-off. Include automation bias awareness in AI literacy training for affected roles.

Severity — 🔴 High

Frameworks — NIST AI RMF, EU AI Act, SR 11-7

---

Risk — Insufficient override and feedback mechanisms

Impact — Without structured channels for staff to flag incorrect or harmful AI outputs, errors compound undetected — degrading model utility and increasing compliance exposure over time.

Mitigation — Build human feedback loops into every Cohere-powered workflow (thumbs down, flagging, escalation path). Route feedback to the AI governance team monthly. Use feedback data to inform model performance reporting.

Severity — 🟡 Medium

Frameworks — NIST AI RMF MANAGE, SR 11-7

---

Risk — Accountability gaps when AI and human decisions intersect

Impact — Unclear ownership of outcomes in human-AI collaborative workflows creates compliance and audit risk — especially where adverse member outcomes occur.

Mitigation — Define decision accountability in RACI documentation for each AI-assisted workflow. Capture AI involvement in audit trails. Ensure adverse action notices comply with ECOA and FCRA requirements where applicable.

Severity — 🟢 Low

Frameworks — ECOA, FCRA, SR 11-7

